column168: A 29 piece shipment was tendered to us from UPS in JNU on Aug. 31st.  AWB 7177 5664 stated we were given 27 boxes and 2 bags.  A shippers endorsement was signed stating that there were no unauthorized explosive, incendiaries, or other destructive substances or items.  Cargo agent accepting shipment exempted this shipment for a freighter aircraft only, so did not see boxes.  Warehouse agent put lot label and Freighter only sticker on a side of box with only directional labels.  Warehouse lead noticed the Haz Mat labels upon loading in the belly of the aircraft.  The shipment was bumped and sent back to the cargo office for more research.    UPS tracking label on package is 1Z RW1 681 03 4312 2418

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was enroute from the shippers location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at Clean Harbor's in transit storage location.  During the time this vehicle was in storage, a routine inspection identified a small amount of a liquid material leaking from the corner of the van trailer  Facility personnel secured the leak and moved the vehicle to the intended waste management facility where the a response team, utilizing appropriate protective equipment, entered the trailer and identifed a cubic yard IBC leaking from the lower corner of the container.  The container was removed from the trailer an immedialtley processed for disposal at the facility.  All clean-up debris was collected and was also processed at the facility.  In addition, the response team cleaned the interior surface of the trailer floor and placed the unit vehicle back into service.
column169: During the course of the response activities it was discovered that the lid of a paint can became dislodged durign trasportation allowing the sharp edge of the can to ouncture the pilethylene liner and body of the IBC allowing the liquid paint to escape from the package.  In order to prevent a recurrence, loading personnel have been re instructed to ensure that all containers packaged must be secure and packaged in such a way to revent realtive movement during the course of transportation.

column168: The incident being reported involved a shipment of 2 part styrenated epoxy resin (UN1866, resin solution, 3,PGIII), with the Part A in 330 gallon IBCs and the Part B in 55 gallon steel drums.  The vehicle corrying the shipment arrived at the Siemens Energy, Inc. facility located at 1901 Briarwood Avenue SW, Fort Payne, AL 35967 at approxomately 13:30.  Upon opening the trailer door, the receiving personnel noted a strong odor of styrene coming from inside the trailer.  Inspection of the containers revealed that there was a 1/2 inch slit at the upper corner of one ot the IBCs, and that an amount of the resin estimated at 1/2 pint had sloshed out through the slit, down the side of the IBC and onto the floor.  There were also a few drops of the resin on one of the adjacent steel drums.  Receiving employee Hoyt McNew carefully removed the leaking IBC as well as the intact one and the steel drums and placed them on the receiving dock.  After speaking with his Safety Department, the driver Joe W. Smith spread absorbent material on the spill and left the Siemens facility.  The leaked material on the IBC and the steel drum were removed using paper towels moistened with methyl ethyl ketone, and a piece of duct tape was placed over the hole, which was above the liquid line, to prevent any further leakage.  The IBCs and drums were then transferred to a secure storage area until needed for production.
column169: It is not known exactly when or how the IBC was damaged.  It was a new container Manufactured in June of 2009.  It was recommended to the driver that there be nspections made at any loading or transfer points in the future to prevent leakage during transit.

column168: A box truck containing hazardous waste was enroute from the shipper's location to a Clean Harbor's in transit storage facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantitiies of material for continued transportation  During the transfer operation, the driver identified a small leak that had developed on the side wall of one of the non bulk packages.  A response crew was assembled and after donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the trailer and placed the leaking container into a suitable salvage drum.  The trailer floor was decontaminated and all material collected in response to the release and clean-up operation was placed into the salvage container.  Once the response was completed, the salvage drum was secured and placed onto the trailer for continued transportation to the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the containr was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed.  Upon examination, it appeared that the leak developed when the container rubbed up against another during transportation.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the individual responsible for loading the container has been reinstructed to ensure that each package is inspected and shows no evidence of damage or suspect structual integiryt (e,g, aging, discoloration) and the containers are loaded and secured in such a way that relative motion between packages is prevented.

column168: While being switch at the KCS Port Arthur, TX rail yard, the UTLX 667904 was found leaking lading Propylene Tetramer, class 3 flammable. Foreman moved the car to the South end of track 16, which was a clear track and were no one would come into contact. Distance was kept at greater than 150 feet as called for in the Emergency Response Guidebook. The car initially came from Unionoil Company on 9/03/09 at 0730 into Beaumont by the YBM305-02. The car was transferred to Port Arthur via the YPA300-03 arriving at 1027 on 09/04/09. I spoke with both crews from these two jobs and no one noticed any leaking from this car at point of contact. Terry Basham, Safety, Security and Emergency response Coordinator for Chevron was notified at 1940 and arrived at 2050. Mr. Basham found the bolts on the dome to be loose and the gasket bad. Both were repaired at 2120.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. For non-accident releases (a.k.a. packages or closure defects such as this), shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.

column42: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S., AT OR ABOVE 100 C AND BELOW ITS FLASH POINT (INCLUDING MOLTEN METALS, MOLTEN SALTS, ETC.)
column168: On September 1, 2009 at 14:34 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Wyoming Yard discovered GATX48951, a loaded tank car of Elevated Temperature Liquid, N.O.S. leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2009-09-01-00157). Youngs Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor and a CSXT Hazardous Materials Manager, were dispatched to the scene and found the manway was not secured and the bolts were laying down along with damage to the manway nozzle gasket. Young's personnel replaced the gasket, properly secured the manway and the leak stopped.  Young's representatives decontaminated the car and cleaned up the spilled material.  The car was released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 212  NARRI: 5(5+1+0) X (3+0) = 90
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On September 5, 2009 at 02:20 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Barr Yard discovered ICCX 74012, a loaded covered hopper car of Hazardous Waste Solid, N.O.S. derailed and leaking from the bottom of car. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2009-09-05-001068). Eagle Construction, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the piping and flange under the car came in contact with the ground and dislodged the gasket and pipe. Eagle personnel utilized epoxy mixtures to seal the car and secure with plastic wrap to prevent any further drip. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.    ATARI 2(5+1+1)(2+0)=28  cause code T313
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Wednesday - 9/16/09  •         0830 driver calls to advise a leak coming from the trailer.  He stopped around 6am and advised nothing was leaking at that time.  Nothing was hitting the ground currently – just dripping on the axles and air lines, very slow leak.  However the vapor smell is strong.  He is at the BP (Sam’s Pitstop) in Delco, Nc.  Address is 27157 Hwy 74 – advised driver to stay upwind and keep the area clear of traffic and pedestrians.  He advised he stopped earlier and there was no signs of leaks at that time earlier in the morning.  Truck stop is basically empty right now where he is at.  He is updating the truck stop so they are aware that a spill response team will be showing up.    •         Contacted customer and they asked us to contact a spill vendor but that they had one on back up.  I contacted our vendor who had a team 90 miles out.  I asked the customer if they had any 1 closer to save on some money.    •         13:57pm – product had stopped leaking up to this point but now is leaking again.  Can smell 50-60 feet away – advised driver to get out of the area be where he can’t smell it.  Due to strong vapor smell I advised driver not to place plastic underneath to catch dripping product nor get close enough and to just leave the drips soak into the dirt and will have the response team clean it up later.  Later I learned driver had already placed plastic underneath.  Roughly 2 oz’s spilled on plastic when vendor arrived – still a slow leak rate.  At this point more traffic is coming inbound but not coming close enough to be a concern.  Hinging on notifying the authorities at this point.  Spill Team should be there in less than 30 minutes to assess the scene, give us a recommendation, and doesn’t sound like any immediate health risks.  Driver however mentions a mild sore throat and sinuses as he’s been breathing it for quite some time.  Advised again to stay up wind and distance himself from the area.  Seek medical attention immediately if symptoms persist longer than 30 minutes after being in fresh air.  He didn’t feel like it was anything to be concerned about and that he had had sufficient distance.      •         14:30 – driver advises fire chief is on the scene wanting answers.  Advised spill team arriving any minute now as ETA was 2:30pm.    •         Apprx 14:45 spill team is on site.  Opening doors of trailer which will require truck stop to be evacuated.  Correction it is evactuated in 200 feet in any direction.  The truck parking area closed but the pedestrian vehicle traffic on the other side of the building is still open.  Updated Janet Bonkowski/Ashley/and Barb from PR team.  Driver advised not to talk to media if they show up.    •         16:30 – Driver had disconnected his truck from trailer per my request and staged the bobtail away from the trailer.  During conversation again mentioned sore throat, chest, and sinus’s.  Advised it would be wise to seek medical attention.  Again said he was honestly not conc
column169: A.  Packaging - Shipper will have to make recommendations on the failure of the valve.  Perhaps more frequent inspection or gasket replacement is required?    B.  Training - All drivers on this account will be retrained on what to do in the event of a spill.  The driver involved on this one will go through Performance Enhancement Training to ensure he knows what to do in the event of a spill and what constitutes a safe distance.      C.  The Truck:  We believe the resulting exposure that hospitalized the driver did not come from sitting in the truck.  We believe it was from being to close to the leaking product.  Before the doors of the trailer were opened exposing the vapors from teh rear of the trailer the truck was disconnected.  However we feel appropriate precautionary measures need to be taken.  301 Environmental was used to do the initial decontamination on the tractor.  Many of the drivers belongings have been disposed of like clothes, cooler, etc.  Electronics (TV, DVD, CB) were salvaged after decontamination.  The truck bedding was disposed of and the cloth seat covers and then shampooed twice.  The hard surfaces were cleaned twice with citri-clean in order to remove any potential contaminants.      HMHTTC (our Bulk Spill Vendor) was finally able to identify a Certified Industrial Hygienist at (Phoenix Enviro Corp) who is able to help document and verify the truck is safe and to meet OSHA’s exposure limit which is based off 8 the hour ‘sleeper time’.  He is working on providing me with a quote before doing the work so that we can stop it if deemed too expensive vs. retainment value.      The Plan:  • Swab various surfaces and have them analyzed for direct contaminants – specifically Benzene  • Two 8 hour days of testing will be performed on the tractor.   Each test runs for 2 hours and the detection media is changed out.  That means 4 tests will be performed each day.  It is a specific air testing machine which tests for chloride ions present in the air.    o Day 1:  Test with truck not running – general presence  o Day 2:  Test with truck running – I advised to run the tractor unit with the AC compressor engaged and the heat cranked up (heat generally makes any chemical agitated and moisture from the a/c compressor would react with remnants).    ¿ For anyone who may be confused at the statement of running the AC compressor with the heat cranked may sound odd.  Automakers have a default now when you turn on your defroster, even with the heat cranked, that it will engage the AC compressor which helps defrost better.  Engaging the AC compressor will introduce a small amount of moisture throughout the system which we know reacts negatively with the chemical identified here.  I am unsure if our trucks operate the same but he will ensure the a/c unit is engaged one way or other.  This way we are testing for worst case circumstances.    • The results will be sent to a 3rd party laboratory where the results will be analyzed  • Since the MSDS d

column168: The 1-800-ASHLAND Call Center (ECC) received a call on 09/22/09 at 10:58 EDT from Matt Hogan with Ashland Distribution in Garland, TX reporting a spill of at this facility. The gasket on the lid of the tote was not seated properly causing approximately one pint of the product spill from the top down the side of the tote.  Product was contained on concrete and cleaned up without incident.  No further assistance requested.  Shipper was Ashland Distribution, Houston, TX.

column168: Material handler was loading drums of material for delivery to customer.  After placing drums onto trailer floor, material handler attempted to secure drums for transport.  As material handler was securing drums for transport, he noticed liquid coming from one of the drums.  The drum was immediately moved to a horizontal position to avoid further leakage.  Univar employees contained area immediately surrounding trailer using abosorbent materials.  Damaged drum was placed into an overpack drum, and spillage was cleaned by Univar employees.      Leakage was caused from a 1/4 inch hole in the bottom of the drum.  The hole was the result of setting the drum on a small protusion (1/8" in height) in the floor of the trailer. The protusion was a small bend in a metal plate (part of the trailer floor).
column169: Metal plate on floor of trailer in question is being replaced.  Ongoing inspections of trailer floors for items which could cause a future puncture will be done.  Trailers exibiting hazards of this nature will be removed from service until repairs can be made.

column168: UPS Cartage Services, Inc. personnel were unloading a shipment from a truck, upon its arrival at the Louisville Air Freight Facility.  At least one of the shipments on the vehicle had been flown by an air carrier other than UPS Airlines.  One of the pallets in this shipment, declared as dangerous goods, fell over and the wooden pallet itself splintered.  The entire shipment (3 wooden pallets) was taken to the "package service center" within the hub to recoup the shipment.  At this time, employees noticed the presence of numerous lithium ion batteries without any short circuit protection.  In addition, one of the pallets was found to hold packages of unmarked, unlabeled and undocumented lithium ion batteries.  There was no fire or other incident associated with this discovery.

column168: An odor was noticed coming from a trailer when it arrived to the dock.  The trailer manifest and paperwork was inspected for Haz-Mat shipments.  After determining the trailer contained Class 3 Adhesives, the door was opened to see the extent of the leaking product.  After seeing the amount of the product leaked onto the trailer floor, the trailer door was shut and Chemtrec was called to get an MSDS for the product.  After consulting with the regional safety manager, it was determined that a vendor would be needed to clean up the spill. A qualified vendor was called to come out and perform the clean up.  In the meantime, the product remained contained in the trailer.  The vendor placed the product into salvage drums.  After the clean up was done, the vendor showed where the plywood dunnage had forklift holes thru the plywood causing the leak to occur.  The Damage to the drum was a direct result of forklift damage while loading.  There was a one-inch hole a little more than 3/4 up the drum where the puncture was made.  The vendor said approximately 15 to 20 gallons of the product was released.

column168: Accordiing to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While offloading product at customer facility, the hose burst, which resulted in the releaseof approximately 100 gallons of free product.  The free product affected the concrete surface, migrated into the free standing water leaking from a damaged water faucet at the facility, and ran into the facility's drainage system.  There were no soils or waters of the state affected by the release.  United States Environmental of Memphis, TN responded to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, the customer PennAkem, had applied kitty litter to contain the free product.  United States Environmental used a pressure washer to clean the affected concrete, flushed the impacted drain, and recovered the spent kitty litter.  The drainage system outfall is a ditch area adjacent to the property.  Upon inspection, no free product was detected within the ditch.  Approximately 600 gallons of free product and water were generated during the cleanup.  Disposal will be coordinated in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.    SUPPLEMENTAL REPORT  The following is a supplemental report to Report Number E-2009090375, Tracking Number 476983. Originally, the initial report involved the release of approximately 100 gallons of free product. However, after further inspection, and customer evaluation, it was determined that no more than 30 gallons released. The majority of free product was water, which had released from the damaged water faucet at the facility. As previously reported, the free product affected the concrete surface, migrated into the free standing water, which had leaked from the damaged water faucet, and ran into the facility's drainage system. There were no soils or waters of the state affected by the release.United States Environmental of Memphis, TN responded to perform the cleanup. Upon arrival on site, the customer Penn Akem, had applied kitty litter to contain the free product. United States Environmental used a pressure washer to clean the affected concrete, flushed the impacted drain, and recovered the spent kitty litter. The drainage system outfall is a ditch area adjacent to the property. Upon inspection, no free product was detected within the ditch.  Approximately 600 gallons of free product and water were generated during the cleanup. Disposal will be coordinated in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations. There were no injuries or exposures reported.

column168: The shipment was booked with Hapag-Lloyd for transport on the Hapag-Lloyd container vessel Veracruz Express from New Orleans, Louisana to Cagliari, Italy.    The shipment was declared as: UN2579, Piperazine 68%, Class 8, PG III    The shipper advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel had sailed from New Orleans that the tank in fact contained:  UN2735, Amines, Liquid, Corrosive, NOS (Contains Piperazine), Class 8, PG II.    The shipping papers that accompanied the tank to the marine terminal did not reflect the correct hazardous material loaded in the tank.    The shipper subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.

When first starting the transfer of product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank, product started to drip from the discharge valve on the cargo tank.  A bucket was put under it right away.  It was determined that the packing in the valve was an issue and opening it up all the way would lessen it to a few drips. Unload was completed without further incident. Initial drips went into containment area and was hosed to customer system.
column169: Driver that brought the trailer in for loading should have checked over the packing better before the trailer was loaded and replaced it if necessary.

column168: Driver was transferring product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank that was about 100 ft from where his transfer hose was hooked to their fill line.  Plant operator was monitoring the level of the tank to let the driver know when to shut down.  When he motioned with his hand, driver shut down but by then 4 gallons had overflowed the storage tank into a containment area around the tank.
column169: Driver should have been notified to shut down earlier.

column168: SHIPPER TENDERED PORTABLE TANK, JBKU511001-5/CA2094098, ON 9/18/09 IN OAKLAND, FOR LOADING TO THE HORIZON EAGLE, EA028W. ON 9/22/09 IT WAS BEING LOADED WHEN A LEAK WAS SEEN. TANK WAS LOWERED AND PLACED IN THE YARD. SUPPLIER WAS CONTACTED AND HE PLANNED TO VISIT IN THE MORNING, WEDNESDAY. ON INSPECTING THE LEAK IT WAS A FAULTY VALVE. VALVE WAS ORDERED AND REPLACED ON 9/28/09. WITH THE NEW VALVE, LEAK CEASED AND TANK WAS ROLLED TO THE HORIZON HAWK, HK029W, FOR TRANSIT TO GUAM, IT WAS LOADED ON 9/29/09 WITHOUT INCIDENT.
column169: THERE WAS NO ISSUE WHEN TANK WAS RECIEVED. IN LIGHT OF THIS EVENT, SHIPPER SHOULD HAVE ITS SUPPLIER HAVE A SUPPLY OF PERTINET TANK PARTS OR AN IMMMEDIATE SOURCE TO TIMELY ADDRESS SUCH LEAKS.

column168: It is theorized that a lining failure of the railcar caused the corrosive product to eat a hole through the wall of the railcar near the bottom outlet. Upon discovery of the leak, an empty tank trailer was used to offload the remaining product in the car. An estimated 100 gallons leaked out onto the asphalted surface, and was contained using sand dikes. No product entered any sewer or waterway. NRC Environmental was contracted to clean the spill, and they used an absorbent material to collect the spilled product and packaged it into 12 plastic 55 gallon drums for disposal.
column169: The railcar tank qualification was done in 2004 and the lining had last been inspected in 2006. The railcar lining was due for reinspection in 2011. If the lining is what failed, perhaps a more frequent inspection rate would have detected the problem.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While BAX Global DG Specialist was breaking down a shipment at the BAX Global Toledo Hub, one fiberboard box was discovered damaged. The fiberboard box consisted of four (4), 11-ounce cans, in which one (1) 11-ounce can was damaged.  Apparently, the release was due to improper loading, which resulted in the release of approximately 11 ounces of UN1950 Aerosol, Flammable.  The free product was contained to the box, and contaminated the remaining cans in the fiberboard box. The Bax Global, Inc. DG Specialist performed the cleanup using gloves.  Cleanup involved placing the damaged box into a plastic garbage bag which will be held in the OS&D bay pending internal disposition in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations. There were no injuries or exposures reported.  BAX Global shall be named as the reporting party only.  The generator of the release has yet to be determined.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to improper loading, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  BAX Global Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column17: Enterprise Transportation Company a division of EPCO, INC.
column168: The driver picked up a preloaded trailer from the shipper. He was not allowed to climb on top of the trailer to check that the washout caps or dome lid is secure. He was able to do a slosh test inside the shippers plant and did so. At that time there was no product leaking from the trailer. When he made his turn out of their parking lot and proceeded up Hwy. 146 to his terminal (approximately 1/4 mile) he noticed that product was coming down the drain tube leading from the crash box. When at the terminal it was discovered that the loading operator failed to secure the dome gasket in place before closing the dome hatch. The dome was opened and a new gasket was put back in its place to secure product from any spillage. A slosh test was done again. No leaks were present and the product was delivered to the customer without any further delays.
column169: The shipper should retrain their employee's the proper procedure of closing a dome hatch to insure that the gaskets are in place. Also, they should allow the drivers that are picking up preloaded trailers or live loading trailers the ability to climb up the trailer to inspect the washout caps and the dome area when the shipping personnal are finished loading it.

column62: Forklift Accident; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: A driver was making a pickup of used storage batteries.  While loading a pallet containing 3 batteries with a forklift, 1 battery came loose from the strapping and slipped off the pallet, cracking the case.  Approximately 1 gallon of the battery acid from inside the battery leaked onto the floor of the trailer.  The shipper's emergency response crew was notified and an internal team secured the battery and containerized all spill debris generated as a result of the clean-up activities.  This material was palced into storage pending disposal at a licensed waste management facility.  Once resovled, the battery was resecured to the pallet and the driver proceeded to the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the batteries were accepted for transprotation, loading personnel had secured the batteries to the pallet.  It was during the laoding operation that a battery fell from the pallet.  It is believed that the method used to secure the battery was not sufficient.  Prior to leaving the sit, the batteries were resecured and acepted for transportation.  The shipper was advised to ensure that all containers are agequaktely secured to prevent movement during any phase of transportation.  The driver was re-instructed to ensure this is done before allowing materials to be loaded onto his trailer.

column168: UTLX 205580 was connected to a tank truck during unloading by railroad contractor RSI Leasing, Inc. personnel when product was noted coming from the overflow system on the tank truck.   A tank trailer will only overflow if the scully system is not working properly.  A scully system is used to prevent product overflow while a transload is in progress by automatically shutting down the loading pump when a predetermined level of product is reached inside the tank trailer.   Investigation developed that the scully on the pump was in the over-ride position. All scully over-rides are kept locked at this location to keep any one from over-riding the scully. The third party vendor who calibrated the pump on 9/25/09 did not return the scully over-ride switch to the on position but left in over-ride which allowed product to overflow during loading of the tank trailer.  RSI Leasing personnel were monitoring the transfer process and immediately shut down the system and began containment and remediation of the spilled material.  All spilled material was contained and recovered using absorbent material on hand.  The waste absorbents material was properly packaged and disposed of.  Note:  The "destination" indicated in item 13, 1000 S. Van Dorn Street, Alexandria, VA, is the final rail destination but is only an intermediate point in transportation.  The car was transloaded into trucks for delivery to the actual final receiver destination(s).  This additional destination information is provided due to the fact the format of this form does not allow entry of additional destination information.
column169: Due to the scully system being in the over-ride position an SOP item has been added to require all RSI Leasing operators to ensure the scully system is in the on position prior to commencing each product transfer.

column168: City driver backed trailer to the dock and saw a fluid on the floor leaking.  Only item on trailer that could have been leaking was the 6.1 poison.  We shut the door and set the trailer away from all personnel and awaited an emergency response team.  Once the team cleaned up the spill, we could only see a small dent on the bottom of the drum.  The drum had been protected with dunnage so it is believed the dent happened at the shipper and started a slow leak while riding on the trailer.
column169: Advised the shipper of the dent and asked them to check other drums for similar dents.  We are in the process of re-training city drivers to look at all drums much closer for possible damage or leakage.

column168: Our driver was transferring diesel from one tanker to another due to an equipment failure (one of our trucks).  He was in the process of pumping the product from one trailer to another when the brass ears on one of the pump hoses vibrated loose and the hose detached from the pump.  As a result, product began to spill out of the hose. The driver immediately shut off the pump and then proceeded to run around to the emergency valves and shut them as well.  The driver failed to use his pump hose clamps to keep the hose ears from vibrating loose.  When utilizing a pump on the truck, it is possible for the vibration created from the pump to cause the hose connections to come loose. For that reason we provide hose clamps to keep the ears from becoming loose.  Upon spilling the product, Keystone personnel immediately tracked the product and discovered that the product ran through the parking lot (asphalt) and into a concrete corner of the lot where it soaked into some dirt that had accumulated. There were no waterways or storm drains effected at all.  We then began putting down oil-dry to keep the product from being spread anywhere.  The Dekalb Co Fire Dept was called and arrived at approximately 2330 hours.  Upon arrival, they verified that the product did not leave the parking lot and that no other area or waterways were effected.  The Dekalb County Fire Dept contacted the GA EPD and they determined, based on the circumstances, that they were not going to dispatch anyone to the site.  SWS First Response arrived on the scene at around 0100 hours and began cleaning up the product and the dirt that was impacted.  All of the product stayed on private property and never entered any streets or storm drains.
column169: The driver is required to utilize the hose ear clamps provided so that this type if situation does not occur.  The driver at fault is being retrained on the proper use of our equipment and the standard operating procedures for our company. Bottom line is that human error caused this incident.  We are now looking into buying hoses with locking ears to avoid this from happening again.

column168: On September 15, 2009 two Veolia employees discovered a leaking cubic yard box (IBC), while unloading a straight box truck at the Veolia intransit facility located in Latham, NY.  Approximately 5 gallons of material had leaked onto the floor of the straight box truck. The leaking cubic yard box was broken down into pieces and placed into another cubic yard box for disposal.  The material that had leaked onto the floor of the truck was cleaned up with speedy-dry and absorbant pads.  The clean-up materials were placed into a cubic yard box for disposal. It was later determined that a plastic liner was not used inside the cubic yard box which allowed the material to leak through the fiberboard construction of the box.
column169: The cause of the spill was due to human error.  The cubic yard box was packaged without the use of a liner which resulted in a spill.  As a result of this incident, training has been implemented to help prevent recurrences of this type of incident.

column168: Driver arrived to make the unload. For this offload they were going to be using the customers pump.  Our driver connected to the fill line.  The customer hooked up the pump.  However the customer hooked up the pump in the opposite direction and rather than unloading from our trailer into the customer tank it sucked product out from the customers storage tank and pumped into our trailer.  To further complicate the situation the customer tank we were hooked up to was the wrong one and therefore contaminated the product.  No reaction resulted but the trailer load of product was waste.
column169: Our driver needed to verify the correct tank hook up prior to unloading.  This did not happen and resulted in a contamination.      Customer needs to hook up the pump properly resulting in product flowing in the wrong direction and a release of hazardous materials - recommend retraining this employee.

column168: On September 4, 2009 a shipment of seven drums (one steel and six poly drums) of mercury contaminated waste water was loaded onto a Veolia transport vehicle at the Veolia Port Washington WI facility for shipment to Veolia's Phoenix AZ facility for recycling. Approximately one hour after leaving the Port Washington facility, the driver stopped at a store to purchase some personal items. As a standard practice the driver conducted a walk-around inspection of the vehicle and saw that a small amount of liquid was leaking from the trailer. The driver purchased a plastic wading pool from the store and absorbent materials. He placed the wading pool under the trailer to catch any liquid dripping from the trailer and put the absorbents on the asphalt surface where the material had already spilled. The material was identified as mercury contaminated waste water based on the shipping papers and appropriate notifications were made to NRC and WDNR. A Veolia response crew was dispatched to the spill site and cleaned up the spilled material, placed the leaking container into a salage drum and prepared the solid spill material for shipment to the end disposal/recycling site. While assessing the spill, it was discovered that the side of the steel drum had been dented and water was slowly leaking from a crease in the dent. The drum had not been leaking prior to loading, while in storage at the Port Washington facility. As such it is believed that the drum was damaged while loading the trailer and it did not begin leaking until after leaving the site. A total of less than 2 gallons of water was released. The water contained mercury in a concentration of 180 - 550 mg/kg. Based on this information a maximum of 0.0092 lb. of mercury was released.

column168: The driver of the tanker unit had just made a right turn, his unit was not completely alligned in the left lane he was attempting to turn into. Another vehicle moved in along side the right side of the tanker and stopped as well.  The tanker vehicle began to move forward, in so doing he did not recognize the other vehicle and the right side of the tanker struck the left side of the other vehicle.  The other vehicle's bumper caught on the #5 loading head and sheered off 5 of 8 bolts holding the loading head onto the loading line.  When the driver of the tanker realized the issue, he stopped, got out and utilized his spill kit to begin the clean up of the 13.8 gallons of gasoline that was released.
column169: The driver of the tanker shall employ improved defensive driving techniques.  By ensuring the lane is clear before pulling forward. column168: Prev Spill. Overfilled 20,000 gal AST by 1598 gallons.  Product flowed to AST containment dike, but drain valve was open allowing Diesel to flow to oil/water separator which then overflowed to soil. Estimated 600 gallons or less flowed to soil.  No surface water impact. Reported to VA DEQ.
column169: Eagle’s management and safety teams will work with Petroleum Products to seek a better method of delivery to their ASTs that does not rely upon the OPD to alert the driver that the tank is at 90% capacity.  We will seek to have PPI order deliveries to specific storage tanks that will hold the entire delivery without concern whether or not the delivery will exceed 90%.  This system, although installed with good intent for safety, unfortunately, caused Eagle’s drivers to wrongly rely on automatic shutdown to prevent spills rather than for them to gauge and reconcile capacity to prevent overfill.    As a result of this release event, a payroll insert was sent to every driver to reiterate and clarify Eagle’s procedures.  This will also be the main topic for Eagle’s October Safety Meeting.  Additionally, Eagle believes that transparency among our employees is a great training tool, therefore, we publicize and post every serious safety event to all Eagle employees and require dialogue among management and employees to affect a culture of prevention.

column168: Driver was using 60' of hose and  15 psi to transfer 850 gal of product from the cargo tank into a 1000 gal storage tank with 100 gal in it to start. Tank was in  a garage.  The only way driver could tell the level of the product in the tank was to climb up a ladder to look inside.  During the unload, he went to check the level of the tank but failed to stop the flow of product while he did that.  The level looked pretty close to the top so driver was going to close valve when he got back to the trailer.  When he got there, he looked back and product was coming out of top of the customer tank.  Customer vacuumed up spill and put in drums for disposal.
column169: The driver did not follow proper procedure.  He failed to close the valve while he went to check the level of the tank.  He was brought in to the office to receive performance enhancement training.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was delivering fuel to a customer location when the driver noticed the product coming up and spilling on the ground. The driver immediately shut off the flow of product. Upon further investigation it was determined that the customer had recently put in new tanks and their was water in the tanks to help anchor them into the ground. The order was requested to be filled that afternoon, by then the water would have been removed. Dispatch errored by sending load out too early and driver errored when he did not follow unloading procedures. It was determined that 40 gallons total was spilled, some on concrete, some reaching soil. SWS responded to the scene and Enviro-Pro Tech handled the clean-up of spill and remediation of soil. No product reached drains.
column169: Driver did not follow unloading procedures. Driver did not check stick readings. Driver was terminated as a result of this incident.

column168: Driver was going to use product pump to transfer product from cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  Before he started he thought the bleeder valve on the pump was open, so he closed. column168: Intermodal container NYKU 571749 experienced a lading load-shift which damaged the intermoda! container by removing the entire top portion of the container.  Loaded as undeclared hazmat within container NYKU 571749 were two rubber-wheeled forklifts with propane fuel cylinders which were attached to the vehicles and connected with open tank valves.  Because the fuel tanks were not isolated by closing the valves before shipment, when falling from container NYKU 571749 the fuel tanks became dismounted from the forklift, rupturing the fuel tank line to vehicle and causing the hazmat release.  The valves were closed by KCS first responders, mitigating the hazmat release.                Correction notes.  These changes required because the railreport DOT interface failed. Driver said he started the transfer of product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank with the discharge valve on his cargo tank open 1/3 way because customer said to go slow.  Customer then told him he could open it more so driver opened it 1/2 way.  About 35 minutes into the unload into a tank that was in a building, product started to leak out of a PVC joint in the customer fill line.  The driver stopped the transfer of product.  The driver said the product was going into one tank and then it was supposed to equalize into another tank.  It did not equalize fast enough and the tank meter monitor did not reflect that fact.  It showed plenty of room.  Back pressure caused the fill line leakage.  Driver waited until the tanks equalized and then completed the unload.
column169: Drivers should be instructed to completely close down every so many minutes to let the tanks equalize completely.

column168: Customer was going to transfer product from our cargo tank to the customer's storage tank.  When they opened up the valve on the cargo tank, product dripped out of the bolted discharge assembly on the cargo tank.  They immediately closed the internal valve to stop the leak.  The bolts were tightened and the delivery completed.
column169: The cargo tank had been worked on prior to the load and it appears that the bolts were not tighened like they should have been.

column168: I WAS CALLED TO OFF-SITE AREA FOR A LEAKING PKG IN A PACKAGE CAR. THE DRIVER WAS SITTING AWAY FROM THE TRUCK WHEN I GOT THERE.  SHE HAD GOTTEN PAINT ON HER HANDS & FOREARMS & WAS COMPLAINING OF DIZZINESS & NAUSEA.  PKG WAS ON FLOOR OF TRUCK IN THE BACK (LEFT REAR) AND WAS LEAKING GRAY PAINT.  USING PPE, I CLEANED THE SPILL, PUT ALL DAMAGED MATERIAL INTO A YELLOW DRUM AND TRANSPORTED IT BACK TO THE HUB.  THE ON-ROAD SUPERVISOR WAS THERE AND TOOK KIM TO CONCENTRA MEDICAL OFFICE FOR TREATMENT.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS ON THE OUTSIDE BOX.
column169: APPROPIATE HAZMAT MARKINGS MUST BE MARKED ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX, NOT JUST THE INSIDE BOXES.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: UTLX 953627 (DOT 112J340W tank car) was reported emanating a product odor in the railyard. UTLX 953627 was cordoned off in the railyard awaiting inspection by BNSF responders. BNSF contract responders inspected UTLX 953627 finding a small amount of icing had formed around the B-end liquid valve's closure plug. No liquid release was evident. The B-end liquid valve was found to be slightly open with its closure plug loose. This liquid valve was closed. The closure plug was removed, cleaned, reapplied and tool tightened. Afterwards, no product odor was detectable. The responders also noted that other valve closure plugs were only hand tight and these were tool tightened as well. The valve housing cover was then closed, secured and sealed with seal numbered 008393. Response was concluded by 1945 hrs. CDT, 9/11/09.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column62: Misaligned Material, Component, or Device; Misaligned Material, Component, or Device
column168: A BNSF switch crew reported product odor emanating from UTLX 25389 (DOT 111A60W1 tank car) in the railyard. UTLX 25389 was cordoned off in the railyard and all working switch crews were instructed to shelter inside the yard office complex. A BNSF hazardous material responder inspected UTLX 25389 and reported finding the vacuum relief valve (VRV) as the source of the vapor odor emanating from UTLX 25389. No liquid product release was evident, although it was noted that the top of this tank car had surface corrosion near the base of the manway nozzle. The responder removed the VRV finding the stem bottom pressure seal (O-ring) displaced. The VRV orifice was then plugged and sealed by inserting and securing a carbon steel plug.  Afterwards, no further product odor was detectable. This response was concluded by 2130 hrs. CDT, 9/17/09. A BNSF contract response team was on standby to monitor and decontaminate/clean the tank shell of UTLX 25389. UTLX 25389 was reinspected the morning of 9/18/09 and still found to be all secure. The valve housing cover was sealed with seal numbered SRS 000401. A bleach/water solution was used to decontaminate the top of UTLX 25389 which was completed by 0915 hrs, CDT, 9/18/09.
column169: The shipper, consignee and tank car manufacturer have agreed to remove the vacuum relief valves on the assigned fleet in this commodity service (14 tank cars total) to eliminate the reoccurrence of a similar incident.

column168: It was reported by Quality Distribution personnel that one of thier tankers had origianlly released approximately 75 gallons onf the UN1263 paint onto an asphalt parking lot during transfer operations.  Upon notification of this incident, ERTS dispatched React Environmental to the site for initial response and remediation activities.  Once React personnel arrived on site and met with local regulators, cleanup activities began.  It was estimated that approximately 200 gallons of the material had been released onto the asphalt parking lot.  Granular absorbents and pads were utilized to clean the bulk material from the surface.  Pressure washing activities were conducted to remove any residual product that existed on the parking lot surface.  No storm drains, surface waters, or soils were impacted as a result of this release.

column168: SHIPPER TENDERED CONTAINER, MSKU931268-5/CA2091908,TO OCEAN CARRIER ON 9/25/09 IN LONGBEACH/SAN PEDRO FOR LOADING ON BOARD THE HORIZON RELIANCE, RG238S, FOR TRANSIT TO HONOLULU. THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED ON BOARD AT 1430HRS AND AT 1515HRS IT WAS NOTICE A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID WAS COMING FROM THE CONTAINER. IT WAS DISCHARGED AND A COMPETENT CLEAN-UP COMPANY (PATRIOT ENVIRONMENT SERVICES), WAS CALLED IN FOR CLEAN-UP AND ADDRESSING THE LEAK. VENDOR ARRIVED ON SITE AT 1830HRS LAYED-OUT PLASTIC TO CONTAINED THE SMALL LEAK. CONTAINER WAS OPENED AND DRUMS WERE REMOVED UNTIL SOURCE OF LEAK WAS FOUND. THERE WAS NO BLOCKING AND BRACING, WHICH RESULTED IN TEH DRUMS HAVING MOVEMENT. ALL THE DRUMS WERE ON PALLETS. ON ONE PALLET A NAIL PROTRUDED UPWARD AND PLACED PIN HOLE IN ONE DRUM. ONE OTHER DRUM HAD A VERY SMALL LEAK FROM THE PLUG. BOTH DRUMS WERE PLACED IN OVERPACKS FOR TRANSIT BACK TO SHIPPER TO HAVE SHIPPER REMOVE AND PROPERLY BLOCK AND BRACE.  VENDOR CLEANED UP ABOUT 1.5 GALLONS FROM THE LEAKAGE.
column169: SHIPPER SHOULD INSPECT ALL PALLETS AND DRUMS PRIOR TO LOADING TO ENSURE THERE ARE NO DEFICIENCIES IN EITHER THAT MAY RESULT IN POTENTIAL LEAKAGE/SPILLAGE. AS THE DRUMS ARE LOADED PROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING MUST BE COMPLETED TO ENSURE THE COMMODITY MAKES THE ENTIRE TRANSIT SAFELY.

column168: A BNSF train crew reported KCCX 3255 (DOT 111A100W2 tank car) expelling product from the top fitting area of this tank car during movement. KCCX 3255 was cordoned off in an auxiliary track. The nearby customer/consignee was notified and after inspection, their representative notified BNSF that KCCX 3255 would not be accepted by them for unloading in a leaking condition. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was notified and inspected KCCX 3255. The BNSF responder inspection revealed that the Salco Noryl plastic safety vent was missing its top inspection cap, the frangible disc, the disc retainer,  the surge protector and had two small cracks emanating from the threaded area of the safety vent housing body. Dried spillage on the side shell of KCCX 3255 was observed and no ground impact was evident. The responder closed the open orifice with a PVC pipe plug, sealed the housing cracks with silicone and covered the safety vent assembly with a piece of vinyl/rubber material. The shipper was notified of these safety vent defects. The shipper sent a tank car mobile repair crew to effect repairs. The repair crew was unable to repair and the shipper then sent a replacement Salco safety vent assembly including an appropriate frangible disc to the BNSF for installation. The replacement safety vent was applied by 1800 hrs. CDT, 9/28/09 without further incident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Skid was loaded in the nose of a trailer during the Outbound dock operations at the Con-way Freight terminal in Atlanta GA by an unknown loader.  Drum was later found to be leaking and was recouped into overpack containers.  Visible damage to pail appears to be a gouge from a forklift blade into the lower third of one of the 5 gallon pail causing approximately 3 gallons to leak out and onto another pail and some cardboard dunnage.  Spillage was cleaned up with absorbent material and the leaking pail and the pail that was leaked on were placed into (2) five gallon repack pails.
column169: An investigation into who unloaded and reloaded the shipment should result in the dockworker(s) being identified and issued disciplinary action for improper forklift handling and improper shrouding of hazardous material with plywood dunnage.  Dockworker should be retrained on forklift safety.

column168: Opened trlr to find one plastic 55 gal. drum on rear, on cardboard with a slight odor. When drum was moved a small stain was seen on the cardbord under the drum. column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT.  CHECK BRAKES FOR PROPER AND SAFE USE. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS!  PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING. column168: Customer loaded trailer with approximately 21,000 pounds of Potassium Hydroxide Solution. They asked our driver to go to the waiting area when a leak was discovered.  Our driver immediately placed a 5-gallon bucket in the area the drip was coming from.                                                                               An estimate of 0.5 to 1 gallon of product leaked onto the customer's pavement. Our driver immediately went back to the loading/unloading area and the customer quickly pumped the product back into their tank.  A second truck was sent to the customer to pick up the load, while the first truck was washed and brought back to the terminal.                                                                           It was discovered that the internal valve of the trailer had a defect in it that was not visible until the valve was dis-assembled.  The product had run out of the blemish in the valve and into the skin/body of the trailer.  Product then leaked out through a seam in the stainless steel shell around the trailer.  Defect in valve was not visible to the naked eye. The hole was about the size of a pinhole.
column169: Valves are removed and inspected with every wash.  Any obvious problems are caught right away and the valve replaced.  This was not the case in this instance; there was no way to know the defect existed.  Microscopic cracks or pits may not be visible to the naked eye.  Valves will be filled with water during wash to insure there are no defects.

column168: At approximately 2:00 pm, John Ellis contacted Kevin Kitchen and informed him that Art Nicholson of Pierce Oil had filled red dyed diesel into the fuel tank of the #1 Diesel Fire Pump.  Art indicated that something was wrong since the fuel gauge was not functioning properly.  Art was to dispense 300 gallons of diesel to the tank.  Normal procedure has been to fill the 750 gallon tank to the 715 gallon level.  After dispensing 562 gallons, the fuel guage was not indicating any additional fuel.  At that point Art requested an Outside Operator and John Ellis arrived.  Upon investigation, it was observed that the tank was completely full and excess fuel had exited through the tank vent.  The tank vent goes through the roof of the Raw Water Pump Building.  Diesel fuel exited the vent onto the roof and entered the roof drains.  The roof drains discharge into the raw water pump inlet sump.  Diesel fuel could be observed in the sump.  A vacuum truck was dispatched and removed the diesel fuel from the raw water pumps sump.  The collected diesel and water were then transferred to the fuel oil secondary containment.  After the water and diesel fuel had been placed in the fuel oil secondary containment, approximately 9 gallons of Remediact was mixed in with the water/diesel fuel.  Liquid Remediact™ is a high concentration of live synergistic bacteria, in a remediation liquid, that quickly starts the bio-remediation process.  Based upon the dimensions of the raw water pump sump and the thickness of the diesel on top of the water (12' X 18'  X 0.75"), an estimated 120 gallons spilled.
column169: Fuel guage is being repaired and a review of filling procedures on the fuel tank.

column168: UTLX 205849 was one of eight cars involved in a low speed derailment during switching operations by the knoxville & Holston River Railroad The derailment was a result of human error. The derailment resulted ib the rollover of UTLX 205849 and the leakage of approximately 25 gallons of material form the vacuum relief valve. Amount of loss is derived from the difference between amount loaded at origin and retrieved at destination by the consignee. The release was stopped by an environmental contractor using a plug and dike material. The car was righted and transported approximately one mile to the consignee’s facility for unloading. The car will be send to a tank shop for further inspection and repairs once unloaded. All movements were with the verbal approval of FRA Hazmat and Mechanical Inspectors who were onsite.    MULTIPLE REPORT  UTLX 204261 was one of eight cars involved in a low speed derailment during switching operations by the Knoxville & Holston River Railroad.  The derailment was a result of human error.  The derailment resulted in the rollover of UTLX 204261, shearing off the vacuum relief valve and the leakage of approximately 8179 gallons of material from the vacuum relief valve mount site.  Amount of loss is derived from the difference between amount loaded at origin and retrieved at destination by the consignee.  The release was stopped by an environmental contractor using a plug and dike material.  The car was righted and transported approximately one mile to the consignee's facility for unloading.  The car will be sent to a tank shop for further inspection and repairs once unloaded.  All movements were with the verbal approval of FRA Hazmat and Mechanical Inspectors who were on-site.
column169: The individuals responsible for the human error have received disciplinary actions involving unpaid suspensions and probationary periods.  All members of the KXHR train crews have received education on the cause of the derailment and new procedures and bulletin orders issued to prevent recurrences.

The car will be send to a tank shop for further inspection and repairs once unloaded. All movements were with the verbal approval of FRA Hazmat and Mechanical Inspectors who were onsite.    MULTIPLE REPORT  UTLX 204261 was one of eight cars involved in a low speed derailment during switching operations by the Knoxville & Holston River Railroad.  The derailment was a result of human error.  The derailment resulted in the rollover of UTLX 204261, shearing off the vacuum relief valve and the leakage of approximately 8179 gallons of material from the vacuum relief valve mount site.  Amount of loss is derived from the difference between amount loaded at origin and retrieved at destination by the consignee.  The release was stopped by an environmental contractor using a plug and dike material.  The car was righted and transported approximately one mile to the consignee's facility for unloading.  The car will be sent to a tank shop for further inspection and repairs once unloaded.  All movements were with the verbal approval of FRA Hazmat and Mechanical Inspectors who were on-site.
column169: The individuals responsible for the human error have received disciplinary actions involving unpaid suspensions and probationary periods.  All members of the KXHR train crews have received education on the cause of the derailment and new procedures and bulletin orders issued to prevent recurrences.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported a 'sulfur' odor emanating from tank cars standing in a yard track. BNSF hazardous material responders' inspections revealed no source of this reported odor, although tank cars inspected had small quantities of dried residue sulfur on the tank shell that likely spilled on the shell during the loading/unloading cycles. Later in the morning, one member of the switch crew that initially reported the odor, complained of inhalation symptoms and was taken to a local hospital, treated and released.  At approximately 1700 hrs. CDT, 9/30/09, another 'sulfur' odor was reported in this railyard. The same BNSF hazardous material responders inspections of sulfur ladened tank cars resulted in finding GATX 65013 (AAR 211A100W1 tank car) with a ruptured 165 psi frangible disc. During cleaning the hardened dried sulfur residue from the Salco safety vent assembly (required to replace the ruptured frangible disc), the safety vent assembly incurred damages. The orifice in the safety vent was covered and GATX 65013 was isolated in the railyard awaiting a replacement safety vent assembly. The shipper was notified and sent a replacement Salco Quick Inspect safety vent with the appropriate frangible disc to the BNSF for installation. This safety vent assembly was applied onto GATX 65013 on 10/06/09 without further incident.

column168: Univar driver picked up 5 drums of Waste, Paint Related Materials, from customer Brandom Cabinets.  When driver arrived back at Univar facility, he noticed the lid from 1 of the 5 drums had come off of the drum.  This allowed approximately 5 gallons of material to come free from the drum.  The material spilled onto the pallet, and adjacent drums/ pallet.  A portion of the material also splashed onto the floor and wall of the trailer.  The material was contained and cleaned by Univar personnel using floor dry materials.  The floor dry material, contaminated pallets, and clean up materials were properly packaged and sent for appropriate disposal as waste.  The drums were cleaned as part of the spill clean up process, and subsequently sent for disposal as intended.    The cause of the failure was failure to sufficiently tighten the nut / bolt holding the securing ring properly in place.  This allowed the securing ring to dislodge and subsequently the container lid to come off.
column169: More in depth inspection of closed containers will be done by Univar employees and correction of any inadequately closed containers will be done.  Univar has also consulted with shipper and has received commitment for same from a packaging standpoint.  Univar will also work with shipper to limit thin liquids in open head drums when possible.

column168: File 26109 - On September 17, 2009, a Quality Distribution tractor-trailer was involved in a rollover accident that involved an iso-tank.  Approximately 5 gallons of product were released from a crushed valve on the head of the iso-tank.  Evergreen Environmental was dispatched to the site to perform a product transfer and remediation activities.  Once on site, the area was secured and a tank trailer was connected the iso-tank.  The product was transferred into the new tank-trailer and the empty iso-tank was removed from the site.  Evergreen personnel then used hand tools to remove the butanol contaminated soil from the site.  The waste was containerized for disposal.

column168: NOTE: A FOLLOW-UP REPORT WILL BE SENT ONCE POLICE REPORT DETAILING EVACUATION INFORMATION AND FINAL COSTS HAVE BEEN RECEIVED.  DRIVING EB ON 1290, APPROACHING EXIT 7 FROM CENTER LANE, DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO MERGE FOR EXIT BUT OTHER DRIVERS WOULD NOT LET HIM IN; DRIVER SPED UP TO GAIN ACCESS TO RAMP AND ENTERED CURVING GRADE TOO QUICKLY; FULLY LOADED TRAILER STARTED TO ROLL, PULLING REST OF UNIT WITH IT.  TRACTOR AND TRAILER UNIT STRUCK GUARDRAIL, WHICH SLICED THE TOP OF THE TRAILER OPEN AND PUNCTURED SEVERAL COMPARTMENTS NEAR THE TOP OF THE TRAILER, ALLOWING APPROXIMATED 7,000 GALLONS JET FUEL TO SPILL TO THE ROADWAY, SURROUNDING EMBANKMENT AND DRAINAGE DITCH.  EMERGENCY RESPONDERS ARRIVED ON SCENE WITHIN MOMENTS TO CONTAIN PRODUCT AND ASSIST WITH ACCIDENT.  NO OTHER VEHICLES WERE INVOLVED IN ACCIDENT, HOWEVER SEVERAL VEHICLES WERE "SPLASHED" WITH THE SPILLING JET FUEL.  SURROUNDING AREA WAS EVACUATED AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE AND ROUTE 290 IN BOTH DIRECTIONS WAS CLOSED FOR INITIAL ACCIDENT INVESTIGATION AND CLEANUP.  GRIFFITH ENERGY IS WAITING ON FINAL REPORTS OF EVACUATED NUMBERS AND TIME; FOLLOW-UP REPORT WILL BE SUBMITTED ONCE INFORMATION HAS BEEN RECEIVED FROM EMERGENCY RESPONDERS.  REMEDIATION EFFORTS TO RECOVER THE LOST PRODUCT AND REMOVAL/DISPOSAL OF THE CONTAMINATED SOILS ARE ONGOING BY OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR

column168: A 10 wheel box truck with a number of water treatment chemical products in IBCs and drums was being driven down a steep grade approx. 2 mi south of Roaring Gap,NC when the driver lost control and went off the road. In the shipment were two 550 gal non-specification IBCs with industrial bleach--12.5% Sodium Hypochlorite Solution, a packing group III material. The truck overturned and the IBCs were ejected through the top of the truck and a portion of the cab. The IBCs ruptured as they continued down the side of the mountian 60-100ft. One IBC tank was split in two large pieces and the other suffered a large split near one end. The driver was hospitalized with a broken arm, exposure to chlorine from the bleach, and head trauma. An environmental cleanup company was able to isolate the area, remove 52.76 tons of soil, backfill,seed and restore the area over 2.5 days. The Hwy was closed for 8 hours.
column169: The reccomendations to date  include a change to the customer delivery location to avoid this highway and increased brake maintanence schedule.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While at railyard in Fremont, California, a leak was discovered from the tank car.  Railyard personnel applied sand to create a berm and contain the free product on the asphalt surface.  NRC Environmental Services, Inc. of Alameda, CA was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, free product was contained on asphalt and rail spurs within a 20x65foot area.    No soils and/or state waters were affected by the release.  Apparently the release occurred due to a leak from the sump, as a result of pressure, pending offload.  NRC Environmental Services applied absorbent material to the free product.  The spent material was recovered and containerized into sixteen (16) 55-gallon drums.  Disposal was coordinated by NRC Environmental Services in accordance with local, state, and federal regulatsion.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to pressure within the tank, pending offload, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Kemira Logistics, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

AT FIRST INVESTIGATION I FOUND THAT DID NOT SHOW SIGNS OF BEING WET. HOWEVER A SLIGHT ODOR NON IRRITATING WAS NOTED COMING FROM IT. I PLACED TO PARCEL IN A SPILL BIN AND TRANSPORTED IT TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION AND PROCESSING. UPON THE FINAL INVESTIGATION THE INTERNAL CONTAINER WAS COMPROMISED AND SLIGHTLY LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM. I CONTAINED THE PARCEL AND PROCESSED ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS THROUGH THE DMP.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH AT LEAST 65 PERCENT, BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: On 09/24/2009, our driver picked up a load of Nitric Acid at Geneva Nitrogen LLC and proceded to bring it back to our plant.  While in-transit, the Utah Highway Patrol was notified that liquid was dripping onto the highway.  A DOT unit of the Highway Patrol intercepted and followed our truck and trailer into our plant.    Upon investigation, it was determined that the material was leaking out of the dome lid, getting into the spill well, and coming out the over flow pipe.  We weighed the truck and trailer on our plant scale and the weight was compared to the gross weight at the Geneva Nitrogen plant, and the truck actually weighed 340 pounds more than it did when it was weighed on the shipper's scale.  Based on that information, and the appearance of dome lid, it was determined that no more than a gallon or two escaped.    After the Nitric Acid was unloaded and the tank trailer washed out, it was taken to the truck shop to determine the cause, where it was determined that the dome lid gasket got kinked as the driver closed the dome lid, preventing it from sealing properly.
column169: We replaced the dome lid gasket with a "rope type" gasket that can't get moved out of its proper position by closing the dome lid.  We also changed every other gasket in our fleet that was similar to the one that failed, with the rope gasket.    We also replaced the swing bolts on the dome lid to make sure they performed at optimum ability.

column168: Mine operator and driver were standing at rear of trailer watching tank air pressure and customer tank level.  Approximately 15 minutes into the off-load they observed a rumbling noise; driver looked up and saw Cyanide spraying out of the top of the valve box on top of the trailer.  He immediately shut off the air supply to the trailer and left the area while the air pressure bled off the trailer. After pressure had bled off of the vessel, he went onto the top of the trailer and found that the bolts had worked loose on the flange of the safety relief valve.  He retightened the bolts on the flange, stopped the leak.  Mine Supervisors were called; after they gave the OK to restart the off load, he completed the off- load with out any more problems.  All product except for light misting was on containment.  Containment and trailer was washed down, misted dirt was removed and taken to leach pad.
column169: Physical Contributors: Excessive depth on the containment pad caused the safety relief outlet from the tank to be submerged with product.  Unsupported weight of the safety relief valve hanging on the vertically mounted companion flange; gasket compresses over a period of time. System Contributors: No Procedure or Inadequate Procedure in Place.  Only procedure that relates to the Safety Valve is 5-year Inspection.  New hazard not found in walk around Audits. Trailer is due for 5-year pressure test in 3 months. Incorrect assembly of bolts on flange or time wear on bolts and gasket could be contributors. Pressure testing protocol is also in question. Human Contributors: Driver did pre-trip visual inspection of cabinet area and found no defects during pre-trip and prior to hooking up for unloading at customer site.                                       Recommended Prevention Measures: All Bolts inside cabinet will be re-torqued at VIK inspection annually.

column168: AFTER MAKING THE FOURTH STOP OF THE DAY, A DRIVER SERVICE PROVIDER RETURNED TO THE DELIVERY VEHICLE (PACKAGE CAR #138627) TO FIND SMOKE COMING FROM THE PACKAGE COMPARTMENT.  THE DRIVER CALLED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT. THE VEHICLE WAS ENGULFED IN FLAMES BY THE TIME THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED. AFTER THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED, DEBRIS FROM THE VEHICLE WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN A SEVERELY FIRE-DAMAGED BATTERY-OPERATED SCOOTER FOR MOBILITY ASSISTANCE.  INCLUDED WITH THE SCOOTER WAS A SEVERELY MELTED AND FIRE-DAMAGED ELECTRIC STORAGE BATTERY, BELIEVED TO BE NON-SPILLABLE.  THE ADDRESS DETAILS AND TRACKING NUMBER FOR THE PACKAGE WERE DESTROYED BY THE FIRE.  NO OTHER KNOWN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS HAD BEEN LOADED ON THE VEHICLE.

column62: Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Fire, Temperature, or Heat
column168: THIS INCIDENT REPORT IS BEING FILED FOR A FIRE OF UNKNOWN CAUSE, AFTER WHICH 3 AEROSOLS WERE FOUND IN THE DEBRIS.  ONE AEROSOL APPEARED TO HAVE DISASSEMBLED IN THE FIRE, BUT THERE IS NO REASON TO BELIEVE THE AEROSOLS CAUSED THE FIRE.  DURING THE MIDNIGHT SHIFT AT THE ATLANTA HUB, EMPLOYEES DETECTED A FIRE IN TRAILER NUMBER UPSU 622465, FOR WHICH LOADING WAS NEARLY COMPLETED AND WAS THEN HOLDING 671 PACKAGES.  SINCE THE DRIVER HAD ALREADY CONNECTED TO THE TRAILER, IT WAS EASILY PULLED AWAY FROM THE LOADING DOOR TO SAVE THE BUILDING.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AND EMPLOYEES WERE EVACUATED FOR APPROXIMATELY 20 MINUTES, AS A STANDARD RESPONSE TO THE FIRE.  AFTER THE FIRE EXTINGUISHED, THE DEBRIS IN THE TRAILER WAS FOUND TO INCLUDE AT LEAST THREE AEROSOLS.  ALTHOUGH THEY HAD BEEN DAMAGED BY THE FIRE, SO THAT THE LABELS WERE ILLEGIBLE, THEY DID NOT APPEAR TO BE THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT.  AT THIS TIME, THERE IS NO KNOWN CAUSE FOR THE FIRE, DESPITE THE WORK OF INDEPENDENT FIRE INVESTIGATORS.  UPS FILES THIS REPORT BECAUSE OF THE INCIDENTAL RELEASE OF THE AEROSOL, NOT TO IMPLY THE DAMAGED AEROSOL WAS THE CAUSE OF THE FIRE.

column168: An import shipment from Taiwan within intermodal container HDMU 237742 that was parked in the BNSF intermodal lot was reported leaking anunknown liquid from the container doorway. HDMU 237742 was carefully moved to the on-site containment area. A BNSF hazardous materialcontractor was called to investigate and mitigate the leak source. The contract responders reported that some shrink-wrapped palletized baggedproduct had sustained water damage due to heavy condensation inside this container. Also, several bags had abraded against the container sidewallspilling product onto the container floor which mixed with the moisture inside the container, thus creating the liquid leakage. All lading was removedfrom this container and staged on plastic. The inside of HDMU 237742 was neutralized and cleaned. All non-damaged lading was then returnedinside HDMU 237742, properly blocked and braced. Twenty-five bags (UN specification 5M2/Y23.3/S/09/TW/BA-CR2056) of product with varyingdegrees of damage were placed into over-pack drums for appropriate disposal.

On September 28, 2009, a Thurel Mason Trucking tractor-trailer was involved in an incident that caused the release of a UN1993 roof coating product.  The product impacted an area of asphalt road surface on Interstate 70 WB, near Grand Junction, Colorado, where it began to solidify on the road surface.  On September 29, 2009, HRL Compliance arrived on site to begin remediation activities.  The liquid, free product was removed from the road surface and containerized for disposal.  Storm water control was put in place and the site was secured until more extensive operations could be coordinated.  On October 19, 2009, HRL Compliance returned to the site to finalize the remediation.  The product that had solidified on the road surface was milled up with supervision and direction from Colorado Department of Transportation.  The waste was collected and removed from the site for proper disposal.

column168: Container NJJU 633512 was reported leaking by the Drayman.  Inspection noted inadequate blocking and bracing on a partial load of totes and drums.  4 totes had been secured in place utilizing 2 each 2x4's nailed to the container floor.  There was no protective load division between the totes and the 55 gallon drums stretch wrapped to pallets directly behind the totes.  The metal cage of one of the totes rubbed against the bottom rolling hoop of the adjacent drum, causing a 3 inch long horizontal crack in the rolling hoop.  Estimated 15 gallons of paint was released through the crack.  The drum was patched and placed into a salvage drum for securement.  The flooring was cleaned of the residue and all the freight, along with the salvage drum, was placed back into the original container for delivery to the local consignee.

column168: OUR VEHICLE (UNIT TK#005 AND TLR#K1 21) WAS PROCEEDING STRAIGHT APPROACHING A CURVE   WHEN OTHER VEHICLE (JEEP). IN FRONT OF OUR TRUCK, TRAVELING BETWEEN LANE AND SHOULDER. STOPPED ABRUPTLY WHILE APPROACHING CURVE. OUR DRIVER APPLIED THE VEHICLE BRAKES TO AVOID HITTING THE JEEP, THIS STARTED THE CHAIN REACTION OF THE TRAILER TO SKID AND THE LIQUID TO SHIFT CAUSING OUR VEHICLE TO ROLL ON ITS SIDE. OUR VEHICLE RESTED ON ITS SIDE ON THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD AGAINST A GUARD RAIL.      TRAILER BEGAN LEAKING AT THE DOME LID, WHICH WAS DAMAGED FROM THE FORCE OF THE TRAILER IMPACTING THE GROUND. THE PRODUCT (CREOSOTE) WAS SPILLING ONTO THE GROUND TOWARDS A NEARBY ROAD DITCH; 29,280 LBS WAS RELEASED (APPROX 3.200GALS), WHICH WAS THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ABOVE THE DOME LID OPENING, IT WAS ABOUT THREE HOURS BEFORE PRODUCT STOPPED LEAKING. WE WERE GRATEFUL FOR A CONSTRUCTION CREW THAT WAS WORKING ON A NEARBY BRIDGE (HUEP LONG BRIDGE) THAT DUMPED A TRUCK LOAD OF SAND AND USED A FRONT END LOADER TO MAKE A SAND LEVEE AROUND OUR VEHICLE AND A SAND DIKE IN THE DITCH TO PREVENT THE SPILL FROM LEAVING THE IMMEDIATE SITE.
column169: OUR COMPANY WILL PROVIDE ADDITIONAL TRAINING FOR OUR DRIVERS ON THE CAUSES AND EFFECTS OF LIQUID LOADS SHIFTING WHILE IN TRANSPORTATION.      OUR COMPANY MANAGEMENT WILL CONSULT WITH OUR TRAILER EQUIPMENT PROVIDER TO DISCUSS WHAT TYPE OF ADDITIONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT CAN BE USED TO PREVENT DOME LID FAILURES TRAILER SKIDDING, AND ROLLOVERS.

column168: Driver ran off the road to avoid a head on collision and lost control of trailer.  Trailer overturned and was drug down the road causing the trailer to leak. Clean up was completed by Able clean up technologies out of Spokane Washington in conjunction with IDOT and DEQ.

column168: The truck driver approached curve on US Hwy 40 @ mile marker 246.7 at excessive rate of speed for conditions. (First snow and winter weather of season.) Truck and tanker overturned onto its side. Accident caused damage to fuel cells on tanker, resulting in fracture of tanker and release of 6350 gallons of gasoline over approximately a 4 hour period.  Total gallons being transported at time of accident was 8200. Approximately 1850 gallons were recovered from tanker. Of the 6350 gallons released, 1850 gallons was recovered from the catch basin. Colorado Highway Patrol, Clear Creek Fire Authority, and Belfour Environmental were all notified and responed for clean up.  Released fuel flowed to catch basin on roadway and discharged from catch basin into ravine. Fuel infiltrated ground surface in ravine. No fuel was observed to flow directly into or threaten to flow directly into any waterway. Sorbent booms were placed in ravine below endpoint of infiltration of fuel as precautionary measure. Nearest waterway is the west fork of Hoop Creek.  West fork of Hoop Creek is permanent stream. No product was ever observed on surface water at the time of the release. Fluctuating concentrations of benzene, toluene, ethyl benzene, and xylenes were detected in surface water samples collected at the point where ravine and west fork of Hoop Creek intersect.
column169: At safety meetings drivers are continually reminded to be aware of conditions and surrounding while driving. Using accident as a reference, drivers are continually reminded to remain cautious and use better judgment when tranporting hazardous material.  Additional training was supplied by Federated Insurance.

column168: At approximately 6:45 A.M. on September 16, 2009, approximately 30 gallons of No. 2 fuel oil was released at the Global Petroleum Corp Terminal located at 140 Lee Burbank Highway in Revere, MA.  The release was a result of overfilling of a tanker truck operated by Marchetti Corp. The No. 2 fuel oil was released to the pavement west of the loading rack at bay 14. The release was caused by the carriers driver who overfilled the tanker truck. The transfer of products at the facility is under the control of the carrier.  The carrier driver's access the loading rack via a card activiated system, activate the flow of product and conduct the transfer until complete.     Immediately following discovery of the release, Global personnel contained the release using absorbent pads. A Global representative notified the Revere Fire Department and the Massachusetts Department of Environmental Protection at  approximately 6:55 A.M. and 7:00 A.M, respectively, on September 16, 2009. In addition, Global notified the National Response Center and the U.S. Coast Guard. MassDEP assigned Release Tracking Number 3-28702 to the release. Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was called in to assist with the cleanup which was completed within approximately 3 hours of the release.    NOTE 1 - Global Petroleum Corp has completed this written report at the request of PHMSA. Global does not believe that it is required to make a written report for this incident.  The regulations under 49 CFR 171.16 require that "each person in physical possession of a hazardous material" at the time of an incident must complete a written report.  This spill was caused by the carrier who was in possession of the fuel product at the time the incident ocurred.  Global transfers possession of the product to the carrier at the time the product leaves the loading arm at the loading rack.  As the carrier was responsible for the transfer, and the spill overflowed from the carriers vehicle after the product left the loading arm, Global was not in possession of the product at the time of the incident, and therefore is not required to report under 49 CFR 171.16.    NOTE 2 - Global Petroleum Corp has submitted this report as the facility where the incident ocurred.  There are certain items related to the carrier that Global does not have access to; specifically information contained in items 10, 12, 26, 27 and 28.  To the extent possible, Global has entered the carriers information.  Note that fictitious dates (01/01/1900) were entered in Item 28 for the manufacture date and test date for the tanker to complete this electronic report.
column169: Follow up training was conducted with the carrier driver as a refresher regarding global policies on loading vehicles at the terminal.  The carrier was also contacted regarding the incident.
