column168: A railcar was overloaded with toluene at the D & E Rail Loading Area (TRK-E) resulting in a 8995 lb release to the ground. The operator was relying on his metering equipment to shutdown the movement once full. The meter was inadvertently reset during a temporary stop for gauging. In addition the operator did not tighten the bolts on the railcar gauge hatch as instructed in ITC Rail Loading procedures and the ITC Tank Car Loading Checklist. By not fully securing the gauge hatch, the overflowing liquid toluene did not enter the vapor line as designed. The vapor line is equipped with an auto-shutoff device that immediately stops a movement once liquid is detected. The operator assigned to the rail car did not keep the rail car within line-of-sight and was not in close-proximity as instructed by ITC procedures.
column169: ITC has developed corrective actions to reduce the probability of an accidental overfill and offsite release from railcar loading at the D&E Loading Area.     Shortly after the incident, ITC management carefully reviewed relevant information gathered from the event and made the decision to terminate the loading operator based on failure to follow written procedures.  Operators are trained to properly secure all hatches before loading railcars. To reinforce this critical task, ITC will revise the Railcar Loading Checklists, operator qualification exams and the operating procedure to provide clear and detailed instructions on properly securing the dome hatch prior to loading and after every gauge stop. The proposed revisions will also emphasize the importance of staying in close proximity to the loading railcar.  In addition, all ITC shift supervisors and safety specialists will conduct more frequent inspections of loading operations during day and night shifts.     The D & E loading area has concrete containment with chemical drains that can contain most small spills.  Due to the magnitude of the event, the toluene overwhelmed the containment and flowed out of the south end of the track and onto the ground.  Once outside of containment, the toluene drained into a nearby storm water catch basin.  In order to provide a greater level of protection against off-property releases through storm water culverts, ITC’s Engineering Department is finalizing a plan to divert the storm water catch basins surrounding the D & E Loading Area into an ITC controlled storm water outfall equipped with a gate valve.  The valve operation will be under the control of an ITC environmental operator and will remain closed when facility drainage is not required.

column168: BRENNTAG MID-SOUTH'S TRACTOR TRAILER WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON I-75, WHEN THE VEHICLE LEFT THE PAVEMENT, WHICH DEVELOPED INTO A SINGLE VEHICLE ACCIDENT.  THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED APPROXIMATELY AT 0530 HRS WHICH WAS REPORTED BY A BYSTANDER UTILIZING THE 911 EMERGENCY SYSTEM.  LOCAL FIRE UNITS RESPONDED AND ADMINISTERED FIRST AID TO THE BRENNTAGE DRIVER.  ONCE THE DRIVER HAD BEEN STABILIZED THE FIRE UNIT REVIEWED THE SHIPPING DOCUMENTS AND CONTACTED BRENNTAG SECURITY UTILIZING THE EMERGENCY NUMBER ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENTS.  THIS COMMUNICATION OCCURRED AT APPROXIMATELY 0750 HRS, WHICH WAS THEN REPORTED ON BEHALF OF BRENNTAG MID-SOUTH INC. TO THE REQUIRED GOVERNMENTAL AGENCIES AT APPROXIMATELY 0805 HRS BY BRENNTAG CONTRACTOR LANCE GANT OF CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES.  AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT, FIRE CONSUMED THE VEHICLE AND THE MAJORITY OF THE CONTENTS.  ALL MATERIALS INCLUDING THE REMAINS OF THE VEHICLE WERE REMOVED THE SAME DAY UNDER THE OVERSIGHT OF FLORIDA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION.  THE AREA DIRECTLY IMPACTED BY THE ACCIDENT AND FIREFIGHTING MEASURES WAS CONSOLIDATED AND COVERED WITH POLYPROPYLANE.  THE SITE WAS REMEDIATED AND CLOSED ON 10/29/09 UNDER FDEP GUIDANCE.

column168: The driver was pulling two tanker trailers eastbound on I 80 near the 600 south exit in Salt Lake City UT.  As he was rounding the curve to go to I 15 south bound the rear trailer swung out and hit the concrete barrier on the left and then rolled on to its side.  It was raining and dark because it was 4 am.  The driver was sited for going to fast for conditions.  Because of the force of the roll over on of the pipes on the spray fill line cracked and there was a small leak.  A towel was wrapped quickly around the pipe to stop the leak.  It only leaked for a short period of time (10 minutes aprox).
column169: The drivers actions were reviewed by the companys safety commitee.  The driver was deemed at fault and was terminated.  This was a good reminder to other driver how severe a roll over is for the company.  The accident was discussed in the next safety meeting.

column168: A SINGLE FLAT TIRE OCCURRED ON THE REAR AXLE OF A TRACTOR PULLING A SET OF DOUBLE TRAILERS HAULING SWIMMING POOL CHEMICALS.  THE DRIVER PULLED OVER TO INSPECT THE TIRE AND FACILITATE A REPAIR.  THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO MOVE THE VEHICLE TO A SAFER LOCATION BECAUSE THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD WAS TOO NARROW TO SAFELY REPAIR THE TIRE.  AS THE DRIVER RE-ENTERED THE ROADWAY THE REAR TRAILER SLIDE OFF THE NARROW SHOULDER EMBANKMENT AND ROLLED OVER.  SEVERAL PALLETS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CRUSHED THROUGH THE TRAILER ROOF AND LANDED ON THE EMBANKMENT.  SEVERAL OF THE PACKAGES WERE CRUSHED DURING THE ACCIDENT AND SPILLED.

column168: Driver was returning to the office with approximately 2000 gallon of propane left on the truck. He rounded a right hand turn when the rear right side wheels dropped off the road. The driver over corrected causing the load to shift turning the truck over. As it was   rolling it crossed the oncoming lane and slid over a bank. The accident caused damage to the hose reel and piping to the meter located on the rear of the truck. Approximately 20   gallons of liquid propane leaked due to the break in the piping. The liquid quickly   vaporized. The safety valves on the truck shut stopping all leaks. Only the propane in the pipe, meter and hose reel escaped. No other vehicles were involved and no one was   injured. The driver was taken to the hospital to be checked out then released by the   doctor.   The cab, meter and hose reel on the truck was damaged. The truck was sent to Propane   Trucks, Inc. in Apex NC for repairs. It received $16,865.00 in damages. A section of   guardrail was also damaged. It cost $1567.50 to replace.   One home is located near the area where the accident took place. Two people were home at the time of the accident. Both were taken to a motel until the truck was safely removed then allowed to return home.

column168: Container was. loaded along with other materials for a stock transfer from Brenntag Pacific, Inc (BPI), South Gate, CA,. to Brenntag Pacific, Inc., Fresno, CA. Container was secured by contract carrier Dan Pipkin, prior to departing   BPI South Gate facility.   During transit, driver Dan Pipkin was alerted by a passing motorist that his trailer was leaking a liquid substance. Dan exited the interstate at exit 195 to inspect his trailer and found liquid dripping from his trailer. Upon further inspection of his load, the driver noticed the IBC loaded near the rear of his trailer had developed a vertical split approximately 12 inches in length, down the crease near the corner. The dripping material migrated to the curbing, where soil and absorbent materials were used to create a dike, preventing further migration.   Upon discovery of the leaking IBC, the. driver called in to dispatch to report and set in motion Brenntag Pacific’s emergency response actMties. CURA Emergency Services was notified, who in turn contacted their sub-contractor, Patriot Environmental Services who responded to the incident.

column168: Passenger Browne tendered a gas generator in its original packaging. The passenger declared that a generator was being transported, but did not advice the airline that it had been used. The passenger drained the generator, but residual gasoline was left in the fuel tank. MKE station agent Armstrong tagged the box and directed the passenger to drop the box at the TSA screening point. TSA received the package and as they put it on the CTX belt, the package was tilted and fuel leaked. The side of the box had a stain and there was a strong smell of gasoline coming from the package. TSA turned the box to AE lead agent Ocon. Mr. Ocon recorded all the passenger information, and adviced that the item could not fly and that it had to be confiscated. The passenger said arrangements could be made to have a family member take the package home. Mr. Ocon donated the item back to the passenger. The spill was contained inside the box. The only proof of the leak were the gasoline smell and the stain on the box.
column169: All MKE agents have been made aware of this incident to ensure that they screen packages more closely before they accept them. A Memo has been posted noting the importance of making sure that items being transported comply with transportation requirements.
